{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17528760","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17528760"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T15:46:44+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T15:46:44+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14329"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17584037","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17584037"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T07:36:43+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T07:36:43+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14329"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14329","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14329"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.1,0.58,0.08,0.06,0.18]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7024"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55309"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7024","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7024"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14329"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"40836"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"20"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"40"},{"type":"tags","id":"41"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4256"},{"type":"tags","id":"4272"},{"type":"tags","id":"4932"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"10183"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"16697"},{"type":"contributions","id":"30673"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55309","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/55309"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 30-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a 2% superficial burn on his right forearm following sun exposure at the beach without sunscreen. He has no significant past medical or surgical history and takes no regular medications. He is a non-smoker. He is clinically stable with normal vital signs. The Emergency Department nurse immediately applied cold water to the burned area for 20 minutes.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following correctly describes Jackson\u0027s burn wound model that explains the pathophysiology of burns?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Zone of coagulation, stasis and necrosis","Zone of coagulation, stasis and hyperaemia","Zone of coagulation, necrosis and hyperaemia","Zone of stasis, ischaemia and hyperaemia","Zone of inflammation, coagulation and necrosis"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EJackson\u0027s burn wound model describes the pathophysiology of burns using three concentric zones:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EZone of coagulation\u003C/strong\u003E: The central area of the burn where tissue damage is irreversible due to direct heat injury.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EZone of stasis\u003C/strong\u003E: The intermediate area surrounding the zone of coagulation, characterised by decreased tissue perfusion. This area is at risk of progressing to further damage if not managed properly.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EZone of hyperaemia\u003C/strong\u003E: The outermost area with increased blood flow due to inflammation. This zone typically recovers unless complications occur.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUnderstanding this model is crucial for assessing burn depth and potential progression. Proper management, including immediate cooling with cold water, appropriate dressings, and adequate fluid resuscitation, can help prevent the expansion of the more severely damaged zones.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe other options are incorrect because they do not accurately represent Jackson\u0027s burn wound model:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EZone of coagulation, stasis and necrosis\u003C/strong\u003E: Necrosis is not a separate zone but can occur within the zone of coagulation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EZone of coagulation, necrosis and hyperaemia\u003C/strong\u003E: This option incorrectly replaces the zone of stasis with necrosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EZone of stasis, ischaemia and hyperaemia\u003C/strong\u003E: This option omits the central zone of coagulation and incorrectly includes ischaemia as a separate zone.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EZone of inflammation, coagulation and necrosis\u003C/strong\u003E: This option does not accurately represent any of the three zones in Jackson\u0027s model.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Jackson\u0027s burn wound model describes three concentric zones: coagulation (central), stasis (intermediate), and hyperaemia (peripheral).","Understanding the burn wound model is crucial for assessing burn depth and potential progression."],"references":["Noorbakhsh SI, Bonar EM, Polinski R, Amin MS. Educational Case: Burn Injury-Pathophysiology, Classification, and Treatment. Acad Pathol. 2021 Nov 28;8:23742895211057239. doi: 10.1177/23742895211057239. PMID: 34869832; PMCID: PMC8637691."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"40836"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14329"}},"stemMe